'''Ōsugi Shrine''' (大杉神社) is a small [[Shinto shrine]] located in {{ill|Fujimino City, Saitama Prefecture|ja|埼玉県ふじみ野市|12=draft}}. It was built in {{ill|Meiji 11|ja|明治11th year|12=draft}} (1878). The main shrine is located in {{ill|Inashiki City, Ibaraki Prefecture|ja|茨城県稲敷市|12=draft}}, and the enshrined deity is {{ill|Ōmononushi|lt=Ōmononushi Ōkami|ja|大物主大神|12=draft}}.

== History ==

Ōsugi Shrine was established in 1878 by people working in river transport on the {{ill|Shingashi River|ja|新河岸川|12=draft}} to pray for safe voyages. Since then, it has gathered faith from boatmen traveling the river. It became customary to select two boatmen annually to visit the main shrine to receive a talisman ensuring the safety of their vessels.

== location and Structures ==

The shrine is located on the western bank of the Shingashi River and faces the river instead of the road. The torii gate leans slightly forward, as if bowing toward the river. It is said that travelers on the Shingashi River once threw coins from their boats to pray for safety. The torii gate bears a plaque inscribed with "Ōsugi-gū" (大杉宮).

Even before the shrine was established, the site was used for prayers for the safety of boats and the peace of the village. Behind the small shrine grounds is a stone monument erected in {{ill|Bunsei 9|ja|文政9th year|12=draft}} (1826), which states that the deities of Ōsugi-gū, {{ill|Funadama Shrine|ja|船玉宮|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Suitengū Shrine|ja|水天宮|12=draft}} were enshrined there.

== Festival ==

The shrine's main festival is held annually on {{ill|September 27|ja|9月27日|12=draft}}. During the Taishō era, it was a lively event featuring boat performances and plays.





